<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health-news">HEALTH NEWS</a></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1>Postpartum Depression Can Strike Fathers as well as Mothers</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.healthline.com%2Fhealth-news%2Fcan-fathers-get-postpartum-depression&amp;media=https%3A%2F%2Fpost.healthline.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2019%2F03%2FFather_Baby_Infant_Holding-1296x728-Header-1296x728.jpg&amp;description=Postpartum%20Depression%20in%20Fathers" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/post.healthline.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Father_Baby_Infant_Holding-1296x728-Header-1296x728.jpg?w=1155&amp;h=1528" alt="Postpartum Depression Can Strike Fathers as well as Mothers"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Can new fathers have postpartum depression?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Yes, they most certainly can.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>At least according to a&nbsp;<a href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0192513X19833111" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">research article</a>&nbsp;published in the Journal of Family Issues.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>New parents should be aware of this possibility and doctors should be on the lookout for it, say the researchers.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Information for the study came from blogs, websites, forums, and chat rooms where new fathers were sharing their stories.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In those postings, fathers said they didn’t know that men could have postpartum depression and women who saw the signs were unsure what to call it.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>New fathers were frustrated by the lack of information and that the information they did find focused on mothers.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Just like many new moms, new dads also said they felt overwhelmed, exhausted, and trapped.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Many felt neglected by their wives, the healthcare system, and society. Some came to resent the constant needs of the baby.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The research team, led by&nbsp;<a href="https://www.unlv.edu/people/brandon-eddy" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Brandon Eddy</a>, couple and family therapy professor at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas, acknowledged several study limitations.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The researchers didn’t have access to the fathers to ask specific questions or to verify who they were.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They couldn’t validate if the fathers received a diagnosis of postpartum depression from a physician or mental health professional.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They also had no way of knowing if the fathers had experienced depression before, or if it was present before the baby was born.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Mounting evidence</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Like women, men can develop depression.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>But there’s no specific measurement to assess postpartum depression in fathers as there is for mothers.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This isn’t the first study to tackle the issue.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A&nbsp;<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/133/5/836.long" target="_blank">2014 longitudinal, population-based study</a>&nbsp;noted that the rate of depression in fathers worldwide ranges from 5 to 10 percent. The study found that the rate is higher among fathers who don’t live with their children. Also, men who live with their children show increasing depressive symptoms as their kids grow to age 5.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A&nbsp;<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14675298" target="_blank">2004 review of studiesTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;found that paternal depression ranged anywhere from 1.2 to 25.5 percent in the sampled communities. But depression among men whose partners had postpartum depression jumped to 24 to 50 percent.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/postpartum-depression/symptoms-causes/syc-20376617" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mayo Clinic</a>, fathers who are young, have a history of depression, or have relationship or financial problems are most at risk of postpartum depression.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Doctors see it in clinical practice</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Dr. Michael Brodsky is&nbsp;<a href="https://www.lacare.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">LA Care Health Plan’s</a>&nbsp;medical director for behavioral health and social services in California.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Brodsky told Healthline that being a qualitative study, this particular research doesn’t say much about how many men are affected by postpartum depression or how long it lasts.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“But the study does a good job of describing the sorts of themes that come up when depressed new fathers write about their experiences on the internet,” he said.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Brodsky explained that the study confirms what he sees in clinical practice all the time.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Young men of reproductive age who, while seeking to be supportive of their romantic partners and their newborn child, are at risk of feeling discouraged, depressed, exhausted, or overwhelmed by the pressures and obligations of new parenthood,” he said.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As many stressors as there are associated with having a new baby, Brodsky said that other things can factor into a depressed mood.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“For example, job performance may suffer as a result of the sleep deprivation tied to caring for a newborn, leading to increased conflict with supervisors. Or the loss of supportive relationships with friends or relatives may deepen a new father’s sense of depression or hopelessness. These types of stressors may increase the risk of developing depression,” he explained.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Dr. Ilan Shapiro is a pediatrician with&nbsp;<a href="https://www.altamed.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">AltaMed Health Services</a>&nbsp;in California and a fellow of the American Academy of Pediatrics.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>He agrees that postpartum depression in fathers is a reality.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Take lack of sleep, change in the entire dynamics of life, a baby who depends on you and demands a lot of time — putting everything together, the entire family is exposed to this stress,” he told Healthline.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“When you’re chronically stressed, it affects cortisol and other stress hormones. Stress hormones are good, but under continuing pressure and anxiety, it wears down the immune system. We need to be alert to help everybody,” said Shapiro.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Some men are reluctant to talk</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Fathers in the study felt pressure to conform to stereotypical “tough guy” roles and to keep their feelings to themselves for fear of appearing weak.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to the researchers, men are less likely than women to seek professional help for depression.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Brodsky said it’s not easy for men to admit to symptoms of clinical depression or to speak in terms of postpartum depression.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“In some ways, it may be easier for men to talk about depression because some male celebrities have been willing to discuss similar struggles. For example, the pop star Justin Bieber recently has talked about his struggles with depression and seeking treatment,” Brodsky added.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Shapiro said that getting men to talk about the condition is the first step.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“When you’re in a place of postpartum depression, you’re not seeing the light. Everything is negative,” he said. “Moving out of that realm is important for you and your family. Not just for the parents, but for the kids. That’s the biggest motivator. To help your family. If you see changes that are more than usual stress, something is wrong and it’s better to have a conversation.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>ADVERTISEMENT</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
